> ## 📘  "Image" vs "Video"
>
> While you may be interested in changing the bot's _image_, the means to do this is by using the bot's video output, similar to how meeting platforms output a static image as a participant's video when a participant's camera is off.
>
> MP4s and GIFs can be output via [Output Media](https://docs.recall.ai/docs/stream-media).

# Platform Support   [Skip link to Platform Support](https://docs.recall.ai/docs/output-video-in-meetings\#platform-support)

| Platform | [Output Video](https://recallai.readme.io/reference/bot_output_video_create) endpoint | Bot Configuration ( `automatic_video_output`) |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Zoom | ✅ | ✅ |
| Google Meet | ✅ | ✅ |
| Microsoft Teams\* | ✅ | ✅ |
| Cisco Webex | ✅ | ✅ |
| Slack Huddles | ❌ | ❌ |

_\*Outputting video for Teams native bots is currently not supported._

## Choosing an Image   [Skip link to Choosing an Image](https://docs.recall.ai/docs/output-video-in-meetings\#choosing-an-image)

Since meeting platforms have constraints around video output resolution, your image should follow these guidelines to achieve the best quality output:

- The image should be in **jpeg** format.
- The image should be **16:9** and the recommended resolution is **1280x720**.
- The maximum size is **1.3MB**, though we recommend attaching smaller images if possible.

_The maximum resolution that most meeting platforms will accept is 1280x720, so anything larger than that will be downscaled._

Some meeting platforms (i.e. Google Meets) have adaptive participant video screen sizes. To ensure that your image is visible, we recommend the content be within the bounding box shown below:

![The blue box is the area which your content will be visible across all screen sizes](https://files.readme.io/1cacda9bd5140f7a36973025997b98c56ebcd51aad6e72f5a3873daee3b69e06-image.png)

The blue box is the area which your content will be visible across all screen sizes

## Outputting the image   [Skip link to Outputting the image](https://docs.recall.ai/docs/output-video-in-meetings\#outputting-the-image)

There are two different ways to change the bot's video output:

1. Using the `automatic_video_output` configuration when calling [Create Bot](https://docs.recall.ai/reference/bot_create)
2. Calling the [Output Video](https://docs.recall.ai/reference/bot_output_video_create) endpoint

> ## 📘  Which method should I choose?
>
> If you simply want to output an image when a bot is in the call, the `automatic_video_output` is a convenient way to achieve this, since no additional API calls are needed.
>
> For use cases that require more granular control over when the bot's video is updated, you can use the [Output Video](https://docs.recall.ai/reference/bot_output_video_create) endpoint.

### Method 1: Using `automatic_video_output`   [Skip link to Method 1: Using ](https://docs.recall.ai/docs/output-video-in-meetings\#method-1-using-automatic_video_output)

[Create Bot](https://docs.recall.ai/reference/bot_create) has two options for configuring video using the `automatic_video_output` object:

- `in_call_not_recording`
- `in_call_recording`

Configuring these will cause the bot to output video when the bot is in the `in_call_not_recording` and `in_call_recording` states, respectively. You can use both parameters to show a different image depending on whether or not the bot is recording.

Each of these takes the same object parameters:

- `kind` \- The type of data encoded in the b64 string (Currently only `jpeg` is supported)
- `b64_data` \- Data encoded in Base64 format, using the standard alphabet (specified here: [https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc4648#section-4](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc4648#section-4))

Let's say I want the bot to display this image once it begins recording ( `in_call_recording`):

![](https://files.readme.io/57bd15c-Recall_Recording_in_progress.jpg)

To do this, I first need to convert this image to a b64 string using an [online tool](https://base64.guru/converter/encode/image/jpg) or a CLI tool like [ffmpeg](https://ffmpeg.org/).

Once I have the b64 encoded string, I can now provide it as the `kind` parameter in the `automatic_video_output.in_call_recording` config when calling [Create Bot](https://docs.recall.ai/reference/bot_create):

JSON

```rdmd-code lang-json theme-light

// POST /api/v1/bot/
{
  "meeting_url": "https://us02web.zoom.us/j/1234567890",
  "bot_name": "Recall.ai Notetaker",
  "automatic_video_output": {
    "in_call_recording": {
      "kind": "jpeg",
      "b64_data": ""
    }
  }
}

```

Now once the bot joins the call and begins recording, it will automatically display this image:

![Automatically updating the bot's image using `automatic_video_output.in_call_recording`](https://files.readme.io/8ec93d4-CleanShot_2024-04-21_at_15.12.19.gif)

Automatically updating the bot's image using `automatic_video_output.in_call_recording`

### Method 2: Using the [Output Video](https://docs.recall.ai/reference/bot_output_video_create) endpoint   [Skip link to Method 2: Using the ](https://docs.recall.ai/docs/output-video-in-meetings\#method-2-using-the-output-video-endpoint)

If you need more granular control over when the image on the bot is updated, you can call the [Output Video](https://docs.recall.ai/reference/bot_output_video_create) endpoint at any point when the bot is in a call.

The parameters for the request are the same as the automatic video output configuration.

**Example cURL:**

cURL

```rdmd-code lang-curl theme-light

curl --request POST \
     --url https://us-east-1.recall.ai/api/v1/bot/{bot_id}/output_video/ \
     --header 'Authorization: ${RECALL_API_KEY}' \
     --header 'accept: application/json' \
     --header 'content-type: application/json' \
     --data '
{
  "kind": "jpeg",
  "b64_data": ""
}
'

```
